{
  "texts": [
    "We decided to keep mentions (@) and hashtags (#) in the tweets (but without (16) |TP(q i)| = N (q i; Ṫ o, Ṫ e) -|FP(q i; Ṫ o, Ṫ e)| = N (q i; Ṫ o, Ṫ e) -|Pos(q i; b o j, b e j)|.",
    "(17)Precision(q i) = TP(q i) N (q i) = N (q i; Ṫ o, Ṫ e) -|Pos(q i; b o j, b e j)| N (q i; Ṫ o, Ṫ e).",
    "@ and #), as they are often integral to the tweets' sentences (e.g., replacing Trump with @realdonaldtrump).",
    "Retrieval of stories and their fact-checksTwitter users rely on different fact-checking pages to validate tweets, mainly depending on the topic of the respective story.",
    "To keep things simple, we only considered two major fact-checking pages (Snopes and PolitiFact; see [57,71]) We selected these pages because they are known to (i) be highly prevalent on Twitter, (ii) propose clear and quantifiable verdicts about the checked stories [67,87] and (iii) conduct independent and high-quality fact-checking."
  ]
